Adding a warning into the install process that will alert installers that their database is using incorrect (and often default) settings.  For instance, MySQL will default the character set to latin1 instead of utf8.  The error could be similar to the notification that REPEATABLE-READ is no longer supported and the database must be configured to use READ-COMMITTED.  This would help prevent a number of issues related to misconfigured database schemas.

I've attached a sample plugin that demonstrates this error.

Steps to reproduce:
# Login as an admin
# Install the attached plugin
# Create a new user that belongs to the 'confluence-users' group
# Edit the permissions on a space to prevent Add and Remove of Attachments for the 'confluence-users' group
# Add the macro 'gliffy-permission-test' to a page in this restricted space
# Login as the user with the restricted permissions
# Navigate to the space

Expected Result:
Question: Can <username> create an attachment to this page? Answer: No

Actual Result:
Question: Can <username> create an attachment to this page? Answer: Yes

Here is the relevant block of code:
{code}
    @Override
    public String execute(Map<String,String> stringStringMap, String s, ConversionContext conversionContext)
            throws MacroExecutionException {
        User user = AuthenticatedUserThreadLocal.getUser();
        ContentEntityObject thisPage = conversionContext.getPageContext().getEntity();

        // This is the offending call
        boolean canCreateAttachmentOnThisPage = permissionManager.hasCreatePermission(user, thisPage, Attachment.class);

        String username = user != null ? TextUtils.htmlEncode(user.getFullName()) :"Anonymous";
        String answer = canCreateAttachmentOnThisPage ? "Yes" : "No";
        return "Question: Can '" + username + "' create an attachment to this page? Answer: " + answer;
    }
{code}

This also appears to happen for the following calls as well:
{code}
            boolean canEditAttachment = permissionManager.hasPermission(user, Permission.EDIT, attachment);
{code}

